name: sfchronicle
text:
Airbnb filed to go public Monday in a long-anticipated offering that defied the pandemic. Though it will generate billions of dollars for its founders and investors, it’s unlikely to have much effect on the already-hot real estate market.
https://t.co/z1DZSkzsx5

name: sfchronicle
text: The United States now has lost more than 247,000 lives to the coronavirus, a milestone crossed Monday, according to researchers at Johns Hopkins University. https://t.co/TlhUvxkJFv

name: sfchronicle
text: Japanese leaders are considering new public health measures after the country recorded a record number of new cases over the weekend, registering 1,737 infections on Saturday. https://t.co/IlLqyVAX5p

name: sfchronicle
text: Officials began recovery efforts Monday to retrieve a barge that sank in front of a salvage yard in the Petaluma River Sunday morning, sending first responders scrambling to prevent potential petroleum leaks and damage to the waterway. https://t.co/2SwYAFNnN6

name: sfchronicle
text:
A couple of San Francisco residents and a union representing grocery workers are appealing the long-proposed opening of a Whole Foods store in the city’s Western Addition neighborhood.

Story by @Shwanika: https://t.co/XdQAh2Gg6P

name: sfchronicle
text:
California orders new pandemic shutdowns that will curtail many indoor leisure and business activities for nearly 95% of residents as the state seeks to avert the surge in cases that has swelled over the U.S.

Story by @ErinAllday & @DustinGardiner: https://t.co/elTq3LDJmJ
